'''Earthquakes in the Netherlands''' occur mostly in the southeast and northeast of the country,<ref>{{nl icon}} [http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/18519/aardbevingen_in_nederland Aardbevingen in Nederland] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323032728/http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/18519/aardbevingen_in_nederland |date=2015-03-23 }}, [[Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute]]. Retrieved on 17 March 2015.</ref> with mostly [[tectonics|tectonic]] earthquakes in the southeast and [[induced seismicity|induced]] earthquakes in the northeast. The [[Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute]] started with seismic registrations in 1904. The heaviest earthquake was the [[1992 Roermond earthquake]] with a magnitude of 5.8.

== Seismic registration ==
The first time that seismic activity in the Netherlands was registered by the [[Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute]] (KNMI) in [[De Bilt]] was on 26 June 1904.<ref>{{nl icon}} [http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/28675/eerste_seismische_registratie_in_de_bilt Eerste seismische registratie in De Bilt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628200228/http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/28675/eerste_seismische_registratie_in_de_bilt |date=2014-06-28 }}, [[Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute]], 2009. Retrieved on 17 March 2015.</ref>

== Tectonic earthquakes ==
The natural earthquakes that occur in the southeast of the Netherlands are caused by active rifts of the [[European Cenozoic Rift System]].<ref>{{nl icon}} [http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/27377/natuurlijke_aardbevingen_in_zuid-nederland Natuurlijke aardbevingen in Zuid-Nederland] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112162603/http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/27377/natuurlijke_aardbevingen_in_zuid-nederland |date=2014-11-12 }}, [[Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute]], 2007. Retrieved on 17 March 2015.</ref> The [[1992 Roermond earthquake]] in the southeastern province of [[Limburg (Netherlands)|Limburg]] was the heaviest registered earthquake in the Netherlands. It had a magnitude of 5.8 and occurred in [[Roermond]] on 13 April 1992.<ref>{{nl icon}} [http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/27523/aardbeving_bij_roermond_13_april_1992 Aardbeving bij Roermond 13 april 1992] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205220210/http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/27523/aardbeving_bij_roermond_13_april_1992 |date=5 December 2013 }}, [[Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute]], 2010. Retrieved on 17 March 2015.</ref>

== Induced earthquakes ==
Since 1986, there have been around 1,000 [[Induced seismicity|induced]] earthquakes in the northeast of the Netherlands caused by the exploitation of the [[Groningen gas field]] near [[Slochteren]]. The heaviest registered earthquake in the northeastern province of [[Groningen (province)|Groningen]] had a magnitude of 3.6 and occurred in [[Huizinge]] on 16 August 2013.<ref>{{nl icon}} [http://www.knmi.nl/cms/content/22993/aardbevingen_door_gaswinning_in_noord-nederland Aardbevingen door gaswinning in Noord-Nederland], [[Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute]], 2013. Retrieved on 17 March 2015.</ref>
This event count shows a remarkable exponential growth in time, pointing to one event per day in 2025. While moderate in magnitude, the sheer number of events acts as a physical stressor to living conditions and gives an adverse outlook long term on structural integrity of homes and buildings.<ref>[http://121.183.206.200:8080/proto.board/abstractArticleContentView?page=article&journal=eas&volume=11&num=5&ordernum=7&site=korsc], van Putten, M.H.P.M., van Putten, A.F.P., & van Putten, M.J.A.M., 2016, Earthquakes and Structures, 11, 861</ref>

